Author-Name: Narayan Janakiraman 
Author-Name: Robert J. Meyer 
Author-Name: Andrea C. Morales 
Title: Spillover Effects: How Consumers Respond to Unexpected Changes in Price and Quality 
Abstract:
 This article examines how unexpected changes in the marketing mix of one
 product in a retail setting can influence demand for other, unrelated,
 items. Results from two laboratory studies show that spillover effects can
 occur in response to both positive and negative changes in either the
 price or quality of a product, such that positive changes increase total
 spending on other items and negative changes reduce it. The results also
 demonstrate that an attributional process underlies these effects,
 indicating that consumers experience specific affective responses directed
 at the retailer that lead them either to reward or punish the retailer
 accordingly. (c) 2006 by JOURNAL OF CONSUMER RESEARCH, Inc.. 
